snippet: With 83 percent of the votes counted, interim figures showed the party was in danger of winning a smaller share of the vote than it did in 2009.
abstract: South Africa's long-ruling African National Congress is headed to another big victory in national elections, though it appears to fall short of Pres Jacob G Zuma's goal of two-thirds majority; ANC leads with 63 percent of vote with 83 percent of ballots tallied.

byline.contributor: Alan Cowell contributed reporting from London.

lead_paragraph: With 83 percent of the votes counted, interim figures showed the party was in danger of winning a smaller share of the vote than it did in 2009.

headline.main: A.N.C. Leads South Africa Vote, but Others Gain
headline.print_headline: A.N.C. Leads South Africa Vote, but Others Gain
